      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 28:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. טוב, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 24:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which here, since תּהפּכות are those who in themselves are bad, does not separate, but heightens: perversitates non simplices aut vulgares, sed pessimae et ex omni parte vitiosae (J. H. Michaelis). With אשׁר (οἵτινες), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", this part is brought to a conclusion. Fleischer, Bertheau, and others interpret ארחתיהם, as the accus. of the nearer definition, as σκολιὸς τὸν νοῦν, τὰς πράξεις; but should it be an accus., then would we expect, in this position of the words, עקּשׁוּ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 59:8",
        "children": []
